Project_Bank_Churn_Prediction¶

Background and Context¶

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Data Description¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc.

Data Dictionary¶

  • RowNumber: Row number.
  • CustomerId: Unique identification key for different customers.
  • Surname: Surname of the customer
  • Credit Score: A credit score is a measure of an individual's ability to pay back the borrowed amount. It is the numerical representation of their creditworthiness. A credit score is a 3-digit number that falls in the range of 300-900, 900 being the highest.
  • Geography: The country to which the customer belongs.
  • Gender: The gender of the customer.
  • Age: Age of the customer.
  • Tenure: The period of time a customer has been associated with the bank.
  • Balance: The account balance (the amount of money deposited in the bank account) of the customer.
  • NumOfProducts: How many accounts, bank account affiliated products the person has.
  • HasCrCard: Does the customer have a credit card through the bank?
  • IsActiveMember: Subjective, but for the concept
  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary of the customer.
  • Exited: Did they leave the bank after all?

### Function to plot stacked bar charts for categorical columns
def stacked_plot(x):
    sns.set(palette="nipy_spectral")
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(x, data["Exited"], margins=True)
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(x, data["Exited"], normalize="index")
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.legend(loc="lower left", frameon=False)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Outlier Detection¶

In [38]:
fig, ax_list = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(30,10))  # create 3*2 subplots
fig.subplots_adjust( wspace=0.5, hspace=0.5)    # to increase distance between subplots

cols = ['CreditScore', 'Age',  'Balance', 'EstimatedSalary']
row,col = (0,0)
for feature in cols:
    row_count = row
    col_count = col 
    g = sns.boxplot(x= data[feature], ax=ax_list[row_count,col_count]) # boxplot  for given feature
    g.set_xlabel(feature, fontsize = 20)    # set label 
    if(col==1):     # logic to set subplot ax for boxplot
        row = row+1
        col = 0
    else:
        col= col+1
plt.show()

Insights

  • Credit Score shows outliers towers right.
  • Age has outliers at hight side.

But here in the problem, I am not handling outliers replacement for two reasons:

  • Outliers don't appear to be very abnormal or as error
  • Want model learn the special cases and work for outliers also.

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model Objective¶

  • To determine whether the customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  • Predicting a customer exit the bank but he did not exit.
  • Predicting a customer would not exit the bank but he exited.

Which case is more important?¶

  • Predicting a customer would not exit the bank but he exited. This will be a loss to the business and againsts the objective.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negative?¶

  • Company would like to capture all most all the customers hwo are about to leave.
  • Company would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false Negative. Hence, The main focues is to minimize the false Negative or identify the True Positive(i.e. Class 1) so that the Company can identify the maximum exited customers.
In [51]:
def make_confusion_matrix(cf,
                          group_names=None,
                          categories='auto',
                          count=True,
                          percent=True,
                          cbar=True,
                          xyticks=True,
                          xyplotlabels=True,
                          sum_stats=True,
                          figsize=None,
                          cmap='Blues',
                          title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    '''
    ( accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score ) = (0,0,0,0)

    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names)==cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])


    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        #Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy  = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

        #if it is a binary confusion matrix, show some more stats
        if len(cf)==2:
            #Metrics for Binary Confusion Matrices
            precision = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[:,1])
            recall    = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[1,:])
            f1_score  = 2*precision*recall / (precision + recall)
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}\nPrecision={:0.3f}\nRecall={:0.3f}\nF1 Score={:0.3f}".format(
                accuracy,precision,recall,f1_score)
        else:
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}".format(accuracy)
    else:
        stats_text = ""


    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize==None:
        #Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks==False:
        #Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories=False


    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(cf,annot=box_labels,fmt="",cmap=cmap,cbar=cbar,xticklabels=categories,yticklabels=categories)

    if xyplotlabels:
        plt.ylabel('True label')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted label' + stats_text)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(stats_text)
    
    if title:
        plt.title(title)
    if sum_stats:
        if len(cf)==2:
            return ( accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score )

Model Building¶

Model - 1¶

  • Fully connected network with ReLu activation.
  • The NN takes a vector of length 12 as input.
  • For each customer inf, the final layer will output a probability distribution (sigmoid activation function) to predict if particular customer will exit or not exit in next 6 months.

Model Definition - Adding layers [layers and activations]

  • Input layer with 12 inputs
  • First hidden layer has 16 neutrons.
  • Second hidden layer has 32 neutrons.
  • The given problem is Binary classification problem so sigmoid function is used in the output layer.

Model Performance Improvement¶

Which metric is important

Model Objective

  • To determine whether the customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  • Predicting a customer exit the bank but he did not exit.[False Positive]
  • Predicting a customer would not exit the bank but he exited.[False Negative]

Which Error is more costly to Business ?

  • Predicting a customer would not exit the bank but he exited. This will be a greater loss to the business and is against the objective.
  • Predicting a customer would exit the bank but he did not exit.This would waste some resources but will not have any loss for their business.

Which metric is right for model performance evaluation and why?

  • Company would like to capture most or all of the customers who would exit.
  • Recall metric defines how many true positives are captured among actual total positives. i.e In this case,Recall would define us "Among all the exited customers, how many customers are correctly predicted as exited."
  • Company would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false Negative. Hence, The main focus is to minimize the false Negative or maximize the True Positive(i.e. Class 1) so that the Company can identify the maximum exited customers.

so RECALL is important for this problem.

Optimal threshold

Trying to find optimal_proba_cutoff from the ROC-AUC curve:

  • find the difference between true positive rate , false positive rate with tpr>fpr( in our problem we are more intrested in tpr i.e recall)
  • Arrange the difference in descending order.
  • Find the treshould where the difference is more.
In [61]:
optimal_proba_cutoff1 = sorted(list(zip(np.subtract(tpr1,fpr1), thresholds1)), key=lambda i: i[0], reverse=True)[0][1]

#initialize the model
model3 = Sequential() 
model3.add(Dense(units=12, input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))  # First hidden layer
model3.add(Dense(units=32,activation='relu'))  # Second Hidden layer
model3.add(Dropout(0.2))  # Dropout added
model3.add(Dense(units=32,activation='relu'))  # Third Hidden layer
model3.add(Dropout(0.5))  # Dropout added
model3.add(Dense(units=128,activation='relu'))  # Forth Hidden layer

# Adding the output layer 
# we have an output of 1 node, which is the the desired dimensions of our output (whether customer exit or not)
# We use the sigmoid because we have binary classification and looking for probability outputs.
model3.add(Dense(1,activation='sigmoid'))  # Output layer

#*****************************************************#
#  Model Compilation
#*****************************************************#
model3.summary()
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(0.001)  # optimizer function Adam is defined with learning rate = 0.01
model3.compile(optimizer=optimizer,loss='binary_crossentropy',metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.Recall(),'accuracy']) # metrics recall is used


#*****************************************************#
#  Training [Forward pass and Backpropagation]
#*****************************************************#
# fitting the model

# training data set is split by 0.2 to use as validation dataset.
history3 = model3.fit(X_train,y_train,batch_size=150,epochs=20,validation_data=(X_val,y_val),)

Final Model Selection - Model-3 ROC-AUC Tuned¶

  • From all the metrics summary shown above, model 3 shows better recall scores, good precision score, accuracy score.

    • There a bit balance between False Positives and False Negatives compared to other models.

  • Model3 has more recall and less precision where as model2,model1 have inverse( recall is less and precision is more).
    In such case if recall and presicion are both important for usecase ,usually we can see F1 score. if F1 score is more , that would be considered as good model.
    Here F1 score of model3 is less but almost very close to model2. As Recall is important here , I prefer model3 over other models.

so Model3 can be declared as better model than model2.

Features of model-3 that helped for better rsults

  • Model3 has 4 hidden layers
  • 2 drop outs between layers [ decresed overfit and complexity of model].
  • Less number of epochs [ less computation resources]
  • learning rate is optimal to get smooth curves.

Various metrics of final selected model( model-3 - ROC-AUC tuned )¶

Please find the analysis on different metrics :

  • Accuracy metric : Accuracy formula is (TP+TF)/(TP+TF+FP+FN).
    If the data is imbalanced. this is not good metirc to consider the performance of the model.
    because even though there are huge FP or huge FN , the accuracy score will be more. This is not reliable incase of unbalanced dataset.

  • Recall : Recall tells the overall capture of true +ve among actual +ve. so this is metric of interest in our problem because we want find the people who will exit. False Negatives are most costly than False Positive in this usecase.

  • Precision is less and Recall is considerably more. This is also because of imbalance classes in dataset.

  • F1 Score: F1 Score is primarity harmonic mean of precision and recall. so less value of F1 score is due to less value of precision. This can be used to compare model3 and model2 performances as

    • model2 has less recall and high precision
    • model3 has more recall and less precision IN such case , if for the usecase both precision and recall are important , we prefer the model which has high F1 score. But here recall is more important, so I prefer model3.

Performance:

  • Recall score is better but it can be still improved because 113 False Negatives is still costly to the bank.

  • Precision is low due to imbalanced dataset.

  • As precision is low, f1 score is low.

Possible improvements than can be implemented.

  • Data is imbalanced. so Resampling techniques can be applied to balanced the data and then train the model. But this is not suggestable as this approach would induce lot of junk data.

  • Threshold can be tuned to get the optimal value

  • Hyperparameter tuning can be used to reduce complexity and improve performance.

Conclusion and key takeaways¶

Conclusions

  • The dataset has highly imbalanced. actual +ve class count is very low. This is the reason for inverse behaviour of precision and recall.

  • Data did not show proper correlation between the columns.

  • Threshould can be tuned to increase recall further but that would increase False +ves.

  • Dataset can contain other information like loans, marital status, number of kids etc that would help for better prediction.

Key Takeaways

  • From EDA , below derivations appear from the data.

    • Account Balance,Number of Products,Age, CreditScore numbers show some affect on churn rate</B>

    • Customers with zero and ten tenure have exited less.</b>

      • This implies that people with low tenure may want to retain to check services for some more time.
      • people with more tenure want to retain as they got used to this bank.

    • Customers with mid credit score(600- 700) range exited more.

    • Also customer with high score also exited. This is shown by some unusual raise at the end.

      • Customers with high score might have got some better offers from other providers.
      • Customers with mid credit score might be not satisfied with the current bank services.

    • Germany has more customers who exited bank services than France and Spain.\

    • Female customers exited more.

    • Inactive members exited more.

Suggestions

  • Business can concentrate on Female customers. can provide gender specific offers to attract Female customers.

  • Germany geographical area can be concertrated to check why there is decrese in the numbers.

  • Business can design some offers to make customers active. For example Business can give some offers on some prodcuts from their credit cards to encorage customers use the cards.

  • Customers can plan some offers to retain customers with high credit score.

  • Customers having or not having credit card did not impact churn rate. so credit cards are not having attractive services to retain the customers. Need some measures around this.

  • There are very less customers with 3 or 4 products. Encourage customers to take more products.
